00:45.641 --> 00:49.546
it at all. In fact, I have heard on English case, 
he's the one that got people to make the

00:49.847 --> 00:55.394
recommendations to do it. I don't know if that's 
true or not. I've heard that he's asked several

00:56.255 --> 00:59.620
people to get the board to... He

01:00.258 --> 01:13.613
was a

01:00.258 --> 01:13.613
very good decision-making type person. He was the 
type of person that he maybe couldn't run all the

01:13.633 --> 01:23.244
alternatives through his mind at one time, but he 
could run enough through the decision that made

01:13.633 --> 01:23.244
him pretty healthy. Let's see. Let's go back to 
Austin. Which governors were most supportive of

01:26.144 --> 01:36.179
the work of the engineering extension service?

01:37.061 --> 01:54.868
Other

01:37.061 --> 01:54.868
than local legislators, were there any other 
legislators that were key supporters? Yes. Who?

01:55.892 --> 01:57.616
Senator Jones, I have him. All right. Do you 
remember his first name? I don't. Grant. Grant

02:01.464 --> 02:02.365
Jones, that's right. Any others? Over the state? 
Mm-hmm. Well, of course, we had a lot of

02:07.536 --> 02:12.687
representatives, but I can't call their names 
right now. But, yes, what we, you know, what...

02:16.415 --> 02:18.137
I'll tell you how I handled that thing. Whenever we 
had a budget, whenever they had the House

02:18.157 --> 02:30.770
Appropriations Committee, I made the point that 
each one of those people not only know me, but know

02:18.157 --> 02:30.770
my programs.

02:30.790 --> 02:34.894
I didn't work with the Higher Education 
Committee, because I'm not, you know, I went into

02:30.790 --> 02:34.894
Higher Education. But I made sure that everybody 
on the Appropriations Committee knew me. And at

02:38.839 --> 02:43.924
that time, we all used to make presentations 
before they cut that out at the end. They had this

02:44.731 --> 02:59.511
little representative from,

02:44.731 --> 02:59.511
I don't know, right out of Marlin Falls County. He 
got to be a pretty good friend of mine, but that's

02:59.531 --> 03:05.439
been 15, 18 years. I saw his name in the paper. He's a 
lobbyist now, by the way. They all get to be

03:09.625 --> 03:11.207
lobbyists. He was very much supportive of 
Perkins. Then we had a representative out of one of

03:15.022 --> 03:26.877
those Dallas houses, one of Cedar Hill, I don't 
recall. But he was a volunteer farmer, wasn't he?

03:28.499 --> 03:29.180
So he was very supportive of us. But I didn't do it 
very easily. As you look back, what were your

03:31.463 --> 03:42.256
proudest moments with the Extension Service, the 
highlight events that you now remember? Well, I

03:42.276 --> 03:43.898
guess the highlight, the things enjoyed most 
about it was the ability that we had to bring about

03:44.958 --> 03:53.631
new programs to people in the state of Texas. I was 
also extremely proud of the quality of our work. I

03:57.257 --> 04:02.765
never, it was, I didn't get two complaints about 
our work for 19 years I was there. I think we had

04:05.028 --> 04:06.831
extremely good people.

04:10.355 --> 04:23.331
But my really highlights was I figured that when 
you take an organization with 15 employees and you

04:10.355 --> 04:23.331
end up with 400, you own a self-support basis of a 
million and a half, and you get it up to 39 million,

04:10.355 --> 04:23.331
that was always a good feeling. And we carried, 
when I left that thing, you might be able to know,

04:23.351 --> 04:29.059
when I left that organization, I left over 13 
million in reserves. That's great. Okay, now

04:32.864 --> 04:37.349
let's turn to the amusing side. Can you think of 
some... event that happened that was one of those

04:40.730 --> 05:05.640
Texas unbelievable something that maybe you just 
went wrong something just the electricity went

04:40.730 --> 05:05.640
off or there's one of those I know you won't believe 
this but it really happened can you know I have one

04:40.730 --> 05:05.640
okay I always had a state of the union speech we 
always had an annual conference and I always give a

04:40.730 --> 05:05.640
state of the union message which I always stressed 
the basics And, of course, I had an information

05:06.127 --> 05:11.618
person who would always put my presentation 
together for me. And I'd have slides. And the last

05:13.461 --> 05:20.194
thing I always ended up with was a plate. Well, for 
some reason, I had this damn button in my hand

05:20.214 --> 05:25.123
snapping up something. And I was up there just 
talking like mad. little girl in the front row,

05:29.296 --> 05:31.599
they put my thing in. He said, Mr. Bradley, you're 
already on slide 20. I was punching the slide. I

05:37.327 --> 05:41.352
wasn't even close to the one I was talking about. In 
front of all 400 people, you know. So they had a good

05:44.116 --> 05:45.078
laugh. They all had a good laugh. And of course, I 
come back at them and I said, now, Clare, the reason

05:46.680 --> 05:54.190
I did that, I just wanted to see if y'all were paying 
attention. Okay, now from all of your Aggie

05:54.828 --> 06:05.926
memories, either as a student, an employee, give 
me a funny Aggie story and then maybe a sad or

05:54.828 --> 06:05.926
poignant Aggie story. It could involve anything, 
anybody. Well, the saddest one, I can get that

06:10.533 --> 06:13.658
right off my chest in the beginning. My roommate 
was in combat 21 days and killed, and he was from

06:13.919 --> 06:19.047
Grange, Texas. And

06:19.381 --> 06:35.386
you all

06:19.381 --> 06:35.386
were

06:19.381 --> 06:35.386
roommates for how long? Two years. Two years. 
Sure, sure. Okay, now some good Aggie fun. I guess

06:47.377 --> 07:03.872
the biggest Aggie fun we had was when Texas beat us 
in a Thanksgiving game in 1940 and made the

06:47.377 --> 07:03.872
touchdown 7-0 for 30 or 40 seconds of

06:47.377 --> 07:03.872
play. And we were all hitchhiked into Austin 
because that was in 1940. And so my roommate at that

07:08.336 --> 07:15.983
time, also was from Ukraine, and Bo T. Roach, which 
was about five or six of us, But downhearted and

07:16.874 --> 07:21.540
disgusted with life, I guess to say. But anyway, we 
got out on Congress Avenue and started

07:21.560 --> 07:24.043
hitchhiking. We got picked up right off. Two cars, 
one stopped right behind us. One had this Model 8

07:28.849 --> 07:32.154
Ford with the little rumble seat in the back. I 
don't remember. I was in the rumble seat. And they

07:34.196 --> 07:36.059
kept going out to Congress Avenue. We told them we 
didn't want to get on the highway too late. It was a

07:39.463 --> 07:40.384
dream. They took us out about 10 miles out of town, 
and I'll bet you there was 500 University of Texas

07:40.634 --> 07:47.763
people out there and about 50 Aggies. And they 
would beat the hell out of us. With a paddle? No,

07:53.290 --> 07:54.712
with a fish. Oh, oh, battle. Oh.

07:59.378 --> 08:00.299
That was quite funny. The reason that was funny, 
you'd think you're so damn stupid that you'd get in

08:00.500 --> 08:04.785
a car like that. And the other one pertains to your 
Rice University group. Uh-oh, my freshman year,

08:08.277 --> 08:12.764
you know, we used to rent these cattle trailers to 
take us down to the courtroom. And so our

08:13.705 --> 08:26.205
upperclassmen told us that they wanted us to all 
get together, freshmen, there was a whole bunch of

08:13.705 --> 08:26.205
us to get together, freshmen, and have yell 
practice right there at the entrance of the Rice

08:13.705 --> 08:26.205
Gate. Well, of course, four of the five of us, we got 
out there early, and we was, standing there and all

08:34.567 --> 08:42.435
he wants about damn 15 or 20 of these damn rhizomes 
come out and grab us and take us up to the damn

08:34.567 --> 08:42.435
dormitory room and paint a damn heart on our head.

